The paper describes the development of a robotic system for automated decaking of 3D-printed parts, which involves the use of deep learning for 3D perception, smart mechanical design, motion planning, and force control for industrial robots. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category, which deals with the design, analysis, and control of robots and their applications. Additionally, the use of deep learning for 3D perception suggests that the paper may also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category, which deals with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of visual information from images and videos. The paper may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category, which deals with the processing, analysis, and retrieval of multimedia data, as 3D printing involves the creation of physical objects from digital models. The use of machine learning techniques for the development of the robotic system suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, which deals with the development and application of algorithms that enable machines to learn from data. Finally, the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category, which deals with the analysis, design, and control of complex systems, as the robotic system developed in the paper involves the integration of multiple components and subsystems.
